post_text: Earlier this year, school administration met with the First Selectman, Registrar of Voters and the Monroe Police Department to develop a safety plan when voting takes place in our schools. As part of this plan, we are restricting voters from entering schools and restricting school staff and visitors from entering voting areas from within the school. When voting during the upcoming referendum on Tuesday, May 7th, please enter the voting area using the outside public entrance designated for voters. If you need to enter the school after you vote, please use the designated voting exit, and enter the school using the main entrance. Thank you for your continued efforts with helping to keep our schools safe.

post_text:
Good Morning:

As you may be aware, numerous bomb threats were made to schools across the country yesterday. Today the Newtown Schools received a similar threat. Although reports indicate that these threats were not credible, Sandy Hook Elementary School was dismissed out of an abundance of caution. We have received no such threats in Monroe. We continue to remain in close communications with the Monroe Police Department and officers will have a more significant presence at all of our schools today. Again, no threats have been made to any of our schools. We will continue to monitor events closely throughout the day to keep all of our students and staff safe.

Thank you.

post_text:
Dear Families:

I hope you are finding relief from the heat and humidity we have had over the past few days. The heat has been accumulating in our school buildings and the National Weather Service has issued a Heat Advisory for tomorrow. Given these conditions, we will be on a 2 hour early dismissal schedule tomorrow. The open house for grades K-2 that was scheduled for tomorrow night will be postponed and a new date will be forthcoming from your child’s school. To find a copy of our school schedules, please go to monroeps.org and look under “quick links” on the right side of the screen. Thank you and have a good night.

Jack Zamary
Superintendent of Schools

post_text: The Connecticut Association of School in conjunction with the Connecticut Interscholastic Athletic Association held their annual Michael's Cup Awards ceremony at the Aquaturf Monday night. One athlete and one partner from high schools and middle schools throughout Connecticut were recognized. Masuk's recipients were Jack Crowell and Jack Rose. All partners were also invited to submit an essay explaining the significance of Unified Sports in their lives. A winning essay was chosen at both the middle school and high school levels. Masuk is proud to announce that Jack Rose submitted the winning high school essay and read it to the audience at the Aquaturf.

post_text: Masuk High School's Child Development class went to Jettie S. Tisdale school in Bridgeport to visit their Pre-K program. They have been studying the preschool age in class. The students observed the preschool students and teachers, helped out with learning centers and recess. Students also brought Concept books that they had written in class and read them to the students. The students also donated books so that each preschool child could go home with a new book. Overall, this was a great learning experience for the students and interaction with the community.

post_text: The Board recognized Sean Serafino, Monroe Elementary Teacher, for being awarded the Connecticut Science Teachers Association (CSTA) 2015-16 Excellence in Elementary School Science Teaching Award. This award is bestowed on a teacher who has not only demonstrated excellence in classroom science teaching, but who has also contributed professionally by providing workshops and/or other support for colleagues, had demonstrated dedication to personal and professional growth by participating in conference and workshops, and has been a productive participant in extra-curricular activities and community projects. Mr. Serafino will be honored at the CSTA award banquet on May 4, 2016

post_text:
The Future Business Leaders of America never ceases to amaze me. The FBLA members attending the 54th Annual State Leadership Conference yesterday in Cromwell should be very proud. Seven of the ten award recipients are eligible to attend the National Conference this summer in Atlanta, Georgia. The award recipients are as follows:

• Dylan Condon and Megan Sheridan - 1st place in Community Service Project

• Sarah Gruber, Michelle Rajpolt, and Carolina Sardinha - 2nd place in Marketing

• Diana Wallet - 3rd place in Public Speaking

• Allie Lichvar - 3rd place in Introduction to Business

• Zayne Lawrence - 4th place in Insurance and Risk Management

• Julianna Barker - 5th place in Introduction to Business Communication

• Kayla Wallet for the Who's Who in Connecticut FBLA award

post_text: Coming April 1st and 2nd, the Masuk Theater Department is performing Cards on the Table, an Agatha Christie murder mystery based in 1930s London. The show begins during a fantastic dinner party, but when the host is killed at the end of the party, all those in attendance are the suspects! Over the course of a few days, the superintendent of Scotland Yard, Superintendent Battle, and the crime writer, Mrs. Oliver, must discover who the killer is before they become the next victims.
